               <p>ROBERT CROWE. I lost a great coat on the 30th of May, from <placeName id="t18290611-306-crimeloc1615">Russell-street, Covent-garden</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290611-306-crimeloc1615" type="placeName" value="Russell-street, Covent-garden"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290611-306-crimeloc1615" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290611-306-off1613 t18290611-306-crimeloc1615"></join>, off the box of<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182906110133"></xptr>a glass-coach near the theatre; it was there about two minutes before.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290611-306-person2207">
                  WILLIAM 
                  CRAIG
               <interp inst="t18290611-306-person2207" type="surname" value="CRAIG"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-306-person2207" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-306-person2207" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Bow-street patrol. I took this coat from the prisoner at a quarter before twelve o'clock at night, on the 30th of May; he was running from the carriage, and about three yards from it - I did not see him take it.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q.Where did you first see me? A. At the corner of Russell-street, with four or five others - I saw a man get on the wheel, take it, and give it to you; this is the coat - I called to stop the other man.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was returning home - there were seven or eight persons behind a carriage, and in a moment this coat was thrown upon my shoulder; the gentleman took me, and ran after another person, leaving me with the officer.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18290611-306-verdict1616" type="verdictDescription">
